  <text>
    <body>
      <div subtype="original" type="letter" xml:id="L.3523" xml:lang="en">
        <pb facs="#IMG.1" n="1"/>
        <opener>Dear D<hi rendition="#sup">r</hi> Schuchardt, </opener>

        <p> I received your card today in company with a long letter from Doctor Carolina Michaelis de Vasconcellos who sends me with it her <hi
            rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">Portugiesischer Sprachführer</hi> just published. It seems useful, &amp; is very pocketable. I do not think I have lost, but I cannot at this moment find, the last <hi
            rend="unknown" rendition="#none">separatabdruck</hi> you sent, in which you give <hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">edergo</hi> and another word ending in go which are total strangers to me. Can they be correct? I hardly know what to write to you about as you ask me to spare you all that is unscientific, &amp; I cannot make out what you mean by scientific. You have not answered my questions about <hi
            rend="unknown" rendition="#none">gako &amp; gache</hi>, <hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">gogora</hi> et <hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">à gogo</hi> etc: nor many others. Your dread of resemblances between words is to my mind a defect in your mental vision. Why are latin, Greek and Sanskrit classed as members of one family if not because they <hi
            rend="unknown" rendition="#none">resemble</hi> each other? Resemblance is certainly <hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">a presumption in favour of community</hi> of origin. What a pity all languages were not formed under the supervision of an apostolic succession of omniscient &amp; omnipresent Schuchardts, gifted with infallibility! How widely they would all differ! How little room they would leave for gropers like me to take erratic paths! P<hi
            rendition="#sup">
r</hi>. <persName
            ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.2510">
Rhys</persName> is Principal of Jesus. <persName
            ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.1466">Van Eys</persName> sent me <ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.subjects#S.4157">
            <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">The Academy</hi>
          </ref> of 16 Feb: containing his letter. I have got my Basque library today<note n="1" place="foot"
            type="editorial">Fortsetzung am rechten Rand.</note> really for the first time since Vizella. At Barcelona I<note
            n="2" place="foot" type="editorial">Fortsetzung kopfüber am oberen Rand.</note> coud only make a partial use of it and, that only for a few weeks. </p>
        <closer>
          <note n="3" place="foot" type="editorial">Randnotiz auf der linken Seite.</note>
          <salute>Yours truly</salute>
          <signed>
            <persName ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.1402">E. S. Dodgson</persName>.</signed>
          <dateline>
            <note n="4" place="foot"
              type="editorial">Kopfüber am oberen Rand zwischen erste und zweite Zeile geschrieben.</note> Banyuls sur Mer. P. O. 11 March till the 22<hi rendition="#sup">nd</hi> 1895. </dateline>
        </closer>
        <pb facs="#IMG.2" n="2"/>
      </div>
